tive electrophysiology researchers. Since the introduction of neuroimaging methods such as fMRI (functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging) the related technique of Event Related Potentials (ERPs, a measure of brain activity derived from EEG - the electroencapholgram) has become a mainstay of the human cognitive neuroimaging field. This method allows investigation of the functional and neural basis of abilities such as memory, attention and language, and provides fine-grained information about the time course of cognitive processing.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The aim of the current proposal is to bring together the strong but widely distributed expertise that exists across the UK. At present there are a large number of researchers using similar ERP research methods to investigate similar questions about cognition, but who have very little direct interaction. The seminar series will bring together researchers, producing a web-based directory of ERP researchers in the UK, providing a forum for discussion on-line, and hopefully encouraging continued interaction and collaboration long after the series has finished. The series will also involve a series of meetings and training events, highlighting important methodological advances, and allowing the development of ?best practice? across researcher laboratories.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>15375</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-451-25-4113</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-451-25-4113</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubject